metadata.name: Phantoms #264
metadata.description:
Phantoms is a series of hazy memories of distant places. Some tranquil, others sinister, each scene is as much defined by what is revealed as by what remains unseen.

In this collection I aim to juxtapose hard and soft. Blocky shapes form the core of the compositions. Upon these surfaces, soft textures appear to flow and drip over the sides. Varying levels of opacity, lighting, and fog effects further soften the scenes to create an atmospheric, dream-like quality. By remaining semi-abstract, each of the color palettes are given the space to influence the mood dramatically.

metadata.name: Syzers #355
metadata.description:
Syzers is a generative synthesizer project with sounds altered by Tone JS.

···· On Tuesday, May 17, unsold editions will be burned ····

Visually it consists of 16 layers, in which more than 350 elements are combined randomly, generating synthesizers with unique environments and landscapes.
As for the sound, 40 tracks were recorded with analog synthesizers that were then assigned to each of the modules. These, combined in groups of 4, provide thousands of possible combinations. 
In addition, these sounds will be further modified by code effects that will randomly vary their properties.

Click to listen to the sounds

Many thanks to @Jpupper and @Fipiaggio for help with programming the sound part and @Purespider for the template.

metadata.name: Lost Twins #47
metadata.description:
Individually, the mints of this token are very simple. Each mint generates half of two cube forms, and each half is assigned random hues (in multiples of 10, from 0 to 360). Collectively as a project, this token challenges the approach of looking for "rarities" in a new way. How the cubes are rendered leaves the possibility for multiple mints to potentially join up on the sides with colors that perfect match each other. Will you find your lost twin?

Made in p5js
Created November 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: Subdivisions #74
metadata.description:
As an artist with a background in engineering, I have always been a fan of technical drawings.
Architectural sketches and renderings fascinate me with their ability to visualize the conceptual.

I create generative art for the same reason - to reveal the beauty in an algorithm.

This project represents the division of space using techniques that, for me, call to mind sitting
at a drafting table, straight edge in hand, imagining what might be possible.

You can export a high resolution PNG (5000x5000) by pressing the 'e' key.

Twitter: @jeffpalmer

metadata.name: Squiral Tile’o’rama #16
metadata.description:
Square Spiral Tile’o’rama
(2021)
By Clockwork Feathers

There are three main components to this image generator. The first is the square spiral tile generation algorithm, which is a routine based off of cellular automata algorithms, but instead of having it iterate in the second dimension, the routine simulates the second dimension in computed offsets in a one dimensional array. That array then gets rolled up into a square “tile.”

The second component is a probability based tiling routine that takes in a generated tile routine and then fills in a specified percentage of the larger image with randomly rotated input tiles. This routine is called repeatedly with adjusted probabilities for smaller tiles. 

Finally, there is a collection of color pallet generation functions. There are eight formulas for choosing a color pallet for the generated image, and one is chosen at random for each run.

For more info on me and my creative practice, find me on Instagram @clockworkfeathers and on twitter @ClkworkFeathers

metadata.name: Unknown Squigl #5
metadata.description:
Squigls flowing through the Tezos Blockchain.

Unknown Squigl is created with four different themes: 

Monochrome - Squigls with light shade of random hue 
Complementary - Strokes with complementarish color calculated from background hue
Ukraine - 211° for yellow and 50° for the blue
Grayscale - Random background shade of gray and an opposite shade of gray for the strokes

And a few different versions for offsetting the strokes.

The pixelDensity can be changed with pressing keys 1,2,4 or 8. (8 can be slow!)
Image can be downloaded in live view with pressing key 's'.

Created with P5JS.

hic et squigl / 2022

metadata.name: Antiflow #166
metadata.description:
"Opposites are not contradictory but complementary." - Niels Bohr

The concept of yin and yang is an ancient philosophy about how opposing forces are not only complementary but actually give rise to each other. This idea reverberates through nature, art, and life itself. Now it is at the heart of modern physics. Perhaps this is a fundamental law of nature baked into the very fabric of existence.

Antiflow is an exploration of how balanced complexity can arise from chaos by harnessing the dynamic interplay of opposing forces. To that end we were inspired to create this wildly unique set by mixing modern physics concepts with abstract expressionism and retro 3D primitives.

The aspect ratio is 3:2 to facilitate poster size prints and device wallpapers. Results are presented without borders, noise, or other effects to allow for maximum detail. Feel free to rotate in whatever direction you choose for the best display.

Press "S" to save at a higher definition.
